## Where Things Live

- `CLAUDE.md` — this file. Index-style; do not inline large rule blocks here.
- `CLAUDE.local.md` — personal, gitignored. Use it for per-developer preferences.
- `.claude/rules/` — scoped rules imported above. APEX writes `00-stack.md`, `10-conventions.md`, `20-gotchas.md`. Add your own as `30-*.md`, `40-*.md`, etc.
- `.claude/skills/apex-*/` — APEX-managed skills (recall, reflect, review).
- `.claude/agents/apex-*.md` — APEX subagents (reflector, curator, archaeologist).
- `.claude/hooks/` — shell scripts the hooks call. Edit at your own risk; replaced on upgrade.
- `.claude/settings.json` — hooks + permissions. APEX-managed block delimited inside the JSON.
- `.mcp.json` — MCP server registry, including `apex-mcp`.
- `.apex/knowledge/` — committed: decisions, patterns, gotchas, conventions. Reviewable like any other code.
- `.apex/proposed/` — committed: pending knowledge from the archaeologist/reflector, awaiting human approval.
- `.apex/episodes/` — gitignored: per-session transcripts, redacted at write time.
- `.apex/index/`, `.apex/metrics/` — gitignored, rebuildable.
<!-- apex:section:layout:end -->

<!-- apex:section:rules-of-the-road -->
## Rules of the Road

These are the small set of always-true rules. Project-specific conventions live in `.claude/rules/10-conventions.md`; recurring traps live in `.claude/rules/20-gotchas.md`.

1. **Use the project's package manager.** See "Common Commands" above. Never substitute a different one.
2. **Run the project's test runner before declaring work done.** Tests are the strongest signal APEX has — when they pass, knowledge is validated; when they fail, the failure is captured for reflection.
3. **Prefer reading over guessing.** Use `Read`, `Grep`, and `Glob` to confirm structure before editing. The `apex-recall` skill surfaces past decisions — use it instead of re-deriving them.
4. **Cite evidence.** When you propose a non-trivial change, point to the file, test, or prior decision that justifies it. APEX records evidence-backed changes with high confidence and unsupported ones with low confidence.
5. **Respect APEX-managed sections.** Anything between `<!-- apex:begin -->` and `<!-- apex:end -->`, or between `<!-- apex:section:NAME -->` markers, is rewritten on upgrade. Add your own content outside those blocks.
6. **Corrections are first-class.** If the user says "no, do X instead", treat it as a durable signal — APEX persists the correction so the same mistake is not repeated.
7. **Secrets never enter knowledge or episodes.** The redactor strips obvious patterns at write time, but do not paste API keys, tokens, or `.env` contents into chat.
<!-- apex:section:rules-of-the-road:end -->

<!-- apex:section:retrieval -->
## Recalling Past Knowledge

When a task looks similar to something this project has dealt with before, invoke the `apex-recall` skill (or call the `apex_search` MCP tool) before writing code. Knowledge entries cite their source file and last-validated date — trust recent, evidence-backed entries over your own priors.
